<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Cost Factors</p>
    <h2>What affects stove repair cost in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128293;</div><h3>Boilover &mdash; LA&rsquo;s #1 ignition cause</h3><p>A pot boiling over and flooding the igniter module is the most common source of burner ignition calls in LA. Often resolves with drying and cleaning &mdash; no replacement part. Flat-rate pricing charges you for a part you might not need.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127968;</div><h3>Apartment stoves &mdash; usually worth repairing</h3><p>Older freestanding stoves in LA rentals (Koreatown, Silver Lake, Mid-Wilshire) are frequently repairable for $150&ndash;$300 total. Replacement plus delivery plus installation in a rental unit is a much larger expense &mdash; repair almost always wins.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127991;</div><h3>Brand and part availability</h3><p>Standard brands (GE, Whirlpool, Samsung, LG) have inexpensive igniters and elements available same-day. Viking, Wolf, and Thermador use proprietary burner components at a premium. We quote parts separately so you see the real difference.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128167;</div><h3>Gas vs. electric surface</h3><p>Gas ignition issues dominate LA stove calls and are usually the least expensive repairs. Electric smooth-top surfaces have pricier glass panels to replace. We assess which component failed before quoting the parts cost.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#9889;</div><h3>Infinite switch failure &mdash; urgent</h3><p>A burner stuck in the &ldquo;on&rdquo; position from a failed infinite switch is a fire hazard. We treat this as a priority repair. If your electric burner won&rsquo;t turn off, call immediately &mdash; don&rsquo;t wait for a scheduled appointment.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128204;</div><h3>All burners checked on every call</h3><p>We test every burner while on site &mdash; not just the one that was reported. On gas stoves, we also run a full gas pressure check and leak test before leaving. No hidden safety issues left behind.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a stove, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">For most LA stove calls &mdash; especially apartment freestanding units &mdash; repair wins on cost almost every time.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Unit is under 12 years old</li>
          <li>Single component failure (igniter, element, switch)</li>
          <li>Total repair (labor + parts) under 50% of replacement</li>
          <li>Apartment freestanding stove &mdash; replacement involves delivery and installation</li>
          <li>Luxury range (Viking, Wolf) &mdash; these last 15&ndash;20 years</li>
          <li>Burner ignition issue &mdash; typically very low total cost</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Budget stove is 12&ndash;15+ years old with multiple issues</li>
          <li>Control board cost exceeds 60% of replacement value</li>
          <li>Glass cooktop crack where glass cost approaches stove value</li>
          <li>Parts discontinued with no reliable ETA</li>
          <li>Owner-occupied upgrade planned regardless</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

